abstract: AFTER an April in which rain or snow fell on nineteen days, and a raw, cold wind prevailed on several more. abstract: CHICAGO, June 3. -- Chicago's police were given a strenuous life to-day by the striking packing house teamsters. In spite of the striking teamsters and their friends thirty-three wagon loads of meat were delivered from the stockyards to down-town stations. Before the task was accomplished, however, a score of policemen and rioters had been injured, and fully fifty persons had been placed under arrest.

abstract: Yesterday's dealings on the Stock Exchange, totalling barely 180,000 shares, were the smallest for any one day in the year -- the smallest, indeed, since October of 1900, almost two years ago. abstract: PHILADELPHIA, June 4 -- There was a heavy contraction of business in the local stock market to-day, but prices were fairly well maintained. The intimation that the strike order in the West Virginia bituminous field would go into effect Monday caused all the coalers to sag.

abstract: In the streets and parks of Brooklyn yesterday afternoon there marched a great army, under banners of white, of purple, and of gold, an army of bright-faced children, the Sunday school legions of the Borough of Churches. abstract: FLORAL PARK, L.I., June 7 -- Search is being made for John Walker, who was station agent of the Long Island Railroad Company at Hyde Park. abstract: ALPENA, Mich., June 8.--An excursion train on the Detroit and Mackinaw Railroad, which left here at 7:15 to-day for Saginaw, and consisted of an engine and twelve coaches, carrying more than 500 people, was wrecked at Black River while running forty miles an hour. One man was instantly killed, three were probably fatally injured, and nearly fifty others received injuries of various degrees of severity, ranging from bruises and cuts to broken limbs.

abstract: WASHINGTON, June 10 -- As a result of last night's conference at the White House the Cuban reciprocity fight to-day entered upon a new phase. To-day and probably for the rest of the week the question is one of the backbone of the beet sugar Senators. The Administration men, who have hitherto been conciliatory, have now begun the process known as "putting the screws on."

abstract: CAMBRIDGE, Mass., June 14 -- Commencement week at Harvard starts to-morrow with the baccalaureate sermon by the Rev. George Gordon of Boston in Appleton Chapel in the afternoon. abstract: NEWARK, N.J., June 15. -- There is a scene of rejoicing to-night in the Polish settlement here. Little Abe Blowenstein is home after a three week's absence. abstract: POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y., June 16 -- The college crews assembled here for the boat races of Saturday were favored with good water for this evening's practice. There was a strong flood tide, and the river was as smooth as glass. All the crews were out, and there was seen the unprecedented sight of sixteen college crews representing the six competing colleges, rowing on the river at the same time.

abstract: TACOMA, Wash., June 17. -- Cablegrams received by transportation companies state that the tea markets have opened in China and Japan at unusually high prices. The prices indicate that Oriental dealers and growers are discounting the decreased values given tea in the United States by a reduction of a 10 per cent, duty effective next January.

abstract: BOSTON, June 17. -- Financial circles took their customary holiday Bunker Hill Day. The Stock Exchange was closed, and the banks, under a mutual agreement, also gave their employes a holiday. abstract: GALES FERRY, Conn., June 19 -- The Yale 'Varsity and freshman crews were given practice this evening, rowing up stream for two miles by easy stretches. In the first racing start the freshmen got the jump on the 'Varsity crew by rowing a higher stroke. Both crews were called back after rowing a short distance, and in the second start honors were about even, but the 'Varsity steadily pulled away from the other crew.

abstract: BOSTON, June 19 -- As Walter Green, William Gillette, the actor, arrived from Liverpool on the Cunard steamer Ivernia this morning. When a reporter approached him he smiled and said: "You're up against it now, for I refuse to be interviewed. You know I am never interviewed." Then he yielded the information that he was back in this country to get ready for his season, when he should probably resume "Sherlock Holmes" again.

abstract: This little book is an extremely scholarly and adequate account of a subject the interest of which to lovers of early Italian art is great. abstract: IN the course of excavation for the new sewer along the line of Fort Washington Avenue the workmen opened out this week a large number of human bones as they approached the line of One Hundred and Eighty-first Street. abstract: LOUISVILLE, Ky., June 29 -- Capt. "Sam" Bryant, one of the beat-known turfmin in the country, died of dropsy at his home in this city last night after a long illness. abstract: CAPE MAY, N.J., June 29 -- Harry B. Paul of Camden died at his cottage here last night of congestion of the brain. He was born in Philadelphia, June 11, 1855. He was educated in the schools of Philadelphia, and then entered the office of Gen. Louis Wagner in that city. In 1869 he was apprenticed in the shops of the Caffrey Carriage Company, Camden, and rose to the Secretaryship of the organization.
